{% import "product-components.njk" as pc %}
<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Decisions</strong> standardizes an <strong>explainable, reproducible decision record</strong>
    &mdash; the answer to <em>"why did the system decide this?"</em>. An underwriting finding, an
    eligibility determination, a pricing tier, a moderation call: each is the aggregate of criteria, where
    every criterion has an input, an operator, a threshold, and a contributed outcome. Today every app
    re-invents that explanation as a bespoke table, and the result is rarely reproducible.
  </p>
  <p>
    Web Decisions fixes one thing &mdash; the <strong>DecisionRecord</strong> schema &mdash; and nothing
    else. It is a <strong>schema-only contract: the record shape is the only lock, and there is no
    provider</strong>, because the decision <em>engine</em> is out of scope (that is the proof-of-compliance
    concern, <a href="/backlog/093-business-rule-manager-proof-of-compliance/">#093</a>). Any producer emits
    the same record, so every consumer interoperates.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(79, 70, 229, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #4f46e5; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #4338ca; font-size: 1rem;">Not the engine, not validation, not a span</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      The rule <em>engine + signed-proof</em> machinery (DMN/OPA, hash-chained logs) is
      <a href="/backlog/093-business-rule-manager-proof-of-compliance/">#093</a> &mdash; Web Decisions is the
      <em>result artifact</em> it (or any engine) emits. <a href="/projects/webvalidation/">Web
      Validation</a> owns form-field invalidity (the user's data is wrong), a different layer from a
      business-rule decision. And despite the word, this is not a <a href="/projects/webtraces/">Web
      Traces</a> execution span &mdash; a <code>DecisionRecord</code> is a payload that <em>may</em> be
      traced, not a span itself.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

