{{ pc.standardSection('id="protocol-decision-record"') }}
  <h3 id="how-it-works">Decision Record Protocol</h3>
  <p>
    A producer never bundles a rendering or a store. It emits a <strong>DecisionRecord</strong> &mdash; the
    normalized, reproducible result of evaluating its criteria &mdash; and any consumer reads it. There is
    no provider to resolve: the schema is the entire contract, which is what lets an underwriting engine, an
    eligibility engine, and a moderation engine all feed the same reporting, audit, and explanation
    surfaces.
  </p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
// The schema — the ONLY lock. No provider: the decision ENGINE is out of scope (#093).
interface DecisionCriterion {
  id: string; label: string;
  input: { name: string; value: string | number | boolean };
  operator: string;            // e.g. 'lte' | 'gte' | '≤' — producer-supplied
  threshold: string | number;
  outcome: string;             // the outcome THIS criterion contributed (pass/refer/fail/…)
  reasonCode?: string;
}

interface DecisionRecord {
  subject: { type: string; id: string };       // what was decided (e.g. { type:'loan', id:'L-1042' })
  ruleSet: { id: string; version: string };     // reproducibility — the explanation replays
  criteria: DecisionCriterion[];
  outcome: string;                               // the aggregated finding
  reasonCodes?: string[];
  at?: string;                                   // ISO, when evaluated
}

// 1. Any engine emits the SAME record — the loan app maps its rules-engine result to it.
const record: DecisionRecord = toDecisionRecord(loan, evaluate(loan));

// 2. Consumers interoperate off the schema — no provider, no coupling to the engine.
panel.append(renderDecisionTrace(record));                 // the Decision Trace intent renders it
auditProvider.append(decisionToAuditEvent(record));        // becomes one AuditEvent
report.addSource(record);                                  // a Web Reporting source
  {% endhighlight %}
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-top: 1rem;">
    <li><strong>Schema-only, by design:</strong> there is no <code>CustomDecisionProvider</code> &mdash;
      unlike Lifecycle/Audit/Guard, there is no engine-swap seam to resolve here. The interchange
      <em>is</em> the record. A provider can be added later if a pluggable normalize/render need emerges.</li>
    <li><strong>Reproducible:</strong> every record carries <code>ruleSet.version</code>, so a stored
      decision can be re-explained against the exact rules that produced it.</li>
    <li><strong>Producer-agnostic:</strong> a hand-rolled rules engine (the loan app), a DMN table, or an
      OPA policy all emit the same shape &mdash; the standard does not own how the decision is computed.</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="composition"') }}
  <h3 id="composition">Composition With Other Standards</h3>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong><a href="/intents/decision-trace/">Decision Trace intent</a></strong> &mdash; the UX half:
      the criteria table + outcome + reasons, composing <a href="/intents/status-indicator/">Status
      Indicator</a> for the outcome token.</li>
    <li><strong>Proof-of-compliance (<a href="/backlog/093-business-rule-manager-proof-of-compliance/">#093</a>)</strong>
      &mdash; the engine that produces the record and signs the proof; Web Decisions is its result artifact.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/projects/webaudit/">Web Audit</a></strong> &mdash; a <code>DecisionRecord</code>
      becomes one <code>AuditEvent</code> in the entity's history.</li>
    <li><strong>Web Reporting (<a href="/backlog/350-web-reporting-project/">#350</a>) / Web Compliance
      (<a href="/backlog/351-web-compliance-project/">#351</a>)</strong> &mdash; consume the record as a
      report source / as compliance evidence.</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="status"') }}
  <h3 id="status">Status</h3>
  <p>
    Web Decisions is in <strong>concept</strong> phase; the Decision Record protocol's schema is specified
    here at <strong>draft</strong>. It was surfaced by the loan-origination exercise app
    (<a href="/backlog/317-exercise-app-loan-origination/">#317</a>), whose rules engine already emits this
    exact shape as its proof-of-compliance trace. The reference Decision Trace render ships with it; the
    engine + signed-proof machinery is the separate proof-of-compliance build (#093).
  </p>
  <h4 style="margin-top: 1rem;">Open Questions</h4>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    <li>Does a criterion carry its <em>raw</em> input and a <em>display</em> form, or one value the producer
      pre-formats?</li>
    <li>Nested / weighted criteria (a sub-decision feeding a parent) &mdash; in scope, or flat-only for v1?</li>
    <li>Is the outcome vocabulary open (any string) or should the protocol name a small base set
      (pass / refer / fail) producers extend?</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}
